er’ (  see  Eirik   ). It was introduced into Britain by Scandinavian settlers before the Norman Conquest. As a modern given name, it was revived in the mid 19th century and has remained in use since."]},{"name":"Eirik","meanings":["From the Old Norse personal name <i>Eirikr</i>, a compound of <i>ei</i> ‘ever, always’ (or <i>einn</i> ‘one, alone’) + <i>ríkr</i> ‘ruler’."]}]},{"name":"Gregersson","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Juel, Lars, Viggo.","Americanized form of Danish, Norwegian, and North German   Gregersen  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Gregersen","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Erik, Nels, Nils, Aksel, Bjorn, Dagny, Juel.  German Hans, Detlef, Erna, Hermann, Jurgen.","Danish, Norwegian, and North German: patronymic from the personal name <i>Greger(s)</i> (see   Gregory  )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1702076,"age":21,"year":"1436","julianDay":2245548,"title":"The Engelbrekt Rebellion","description":"Engelbrekt Engelbrektsson, a Swedish mine owner and statesman, led a rebellion against Eric of Pomerania, King of the Kalmar Union. Sweden was upset with the Danes' interference with Swedish exports and unjust collection of taxes. The Engelbrekt Rebellion led to the deposing of Eric of Pomerania and the eventual dissolution of the Kalmar Union.","jurisdictionLevel":3}],"lifeSummary":"When Erik Gregersson Örnflycht was born about 1415, in Granhammar, Västra Ryd, Uppsala, Sweden, his father, Greger Djekn Örnflycht, was 0 and his mother, Mrs. Greger Djaekne, was 27. He married Mrs. Erik Gregersson Örnflycht about 1448, in Uppsala, Sweden. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1481, in his hometown, at the age of 67."},"et":{"abt. 1415–1481":"umbes 1415–1481","1402–1472":"1402–1472","1404–Female":"1404–Surnud","1415–1481":"1415–1481","1404–1482":"1404–1482","1448–1497":"1448–1497","1416–1445":"1416–1445","1390–